nk colonel unit th cavalry regiment commands held th cavalry regiment battleswars indian wars spanish–american war philippine–american war pancho villa expedition world war i charles young march   – january   was the third africanamerican graduate of west point the first black us national park superintendent first black military attaché first black man to achieve the rank of colonel and highestranking black officer in the regular army until his death in  contents  early life and education  west point  career  marriage and family  military service  national park assignments  other military assignments  forced retirement  honors and legacy  military medals  dates of rank  see also  references  external links early life and educationedit charles young was born in  into slavery to gabriel young and arminta bruen in mays lick kentucky a small village near maysville however his father escaped from slavery early in  crossing the ohio river to ripley ohio and enlisting in the fifth regiment of colored artillery heavy near the end of the american civil war his service earned gabriel and his wife their freedom which was guaranteed by the th amendment after the war arminta already knew how to read and write which suggests she may have worked as a house slave before her freedom the young family settled in ripley when gabriel was discharged in  deciding that opportunities were probably better there than in postwar kentucky gabriel young received a bonus by continuing to serve in the army after the war and he had enough to buy land and build a house charles young attended the allwhite high school in ripley the only one there who was afroamerican he graduated in  at the top of his class he then taught school for several years in the new black high school that was opened in ripley west pointedit in  young took a competitive examination for appointment as a cadet at united states military academy at west point he had the second highest score in his district but the top candidate dec